did.unittitle: Engineering Communications & Marketing (University of Michigan) records
did.abstract: Unit of the University of Michigan College of Engineering responsible for producing print and multi-media publications for the college. Records include administrative files and publications, photographs, videotapes, and other material produced for internal and external use to document and illustrate research, faculty, staff, students and alumni of the College of Engineering.

repository.corpname: Bentley Historical Library University of Michigan

acqinfo.p: The records were transferred from the College of Engineering Office of Communications & Marketing (donor no. 8405) beginning in September 1995. An additional 23 boxes were received in 2010.

accruals.p: Periodic additions to the records are expected.

prefercite.p: item, folder title, box no., Engineering Communications & Marketing (University of Michigan) records, Bentley Historical Library, University of Michigan

bioghist.p: The University of Michigan College of Engineering Office of Communications & Marketing serves as an editorial and production office for College of Engineering publications, outreach efforts, special events, and alumni and development activities. Staff members coordinate the production of publications and online content, including research, writing, editing and design. The antecedents of the Office of Communications & Marketing can be traced back several decades to the 1950s when the College of Engineering began publishing a newsletter for engineering alumni. Under the deanship of Gordon J. Van Wylen (1965-1972) the dean's newsletter evolved into several publications, the bulletins Ingenor and Technium and a newsletter which appeared under various names, News, Newsletter, and Newsliner.

In 1990, Interim Dean Daniel Atkins hired permanent staff for the publication effort. Dean Peter Banks moved publications to the College Relations area under Terry Wood, then Assistant Dean and Director of College Relations. In 1993, Brad Canale assumed the position of Executive Director of College Relations with Engineering Communications as a part of that office. In 2011 the College underwent a reorganization and Engineering Communications, now known as Communications and Marketing, became the Office of Communications & Marketing with the Executive Director reporting directly to the Dean of the College and becoming a member of the Dean's Cabinet.

Since 1990, the Office of Communications & Marketing has been responsible for a wide assortment of regular and special print publications and functions. The unit also produces scripts for special events such as commencement, dedications, and award ceremonies. Due to its connection with alumni and development activities, the office has served as an unofficial repository for historical material collected from throughout the engineering campus as well as from alumni.

scopecontent.p: The record group Engineering Communications & Marketing contains records documenting the history of the University of Michigan College of Engineering, particularly the photographic history of the college. Documentation includes memos, correspondence, written scripts for special events, photographs, slides, contact sheets, negatives, one cassette recording and one compact disc. The record group is divided into five series that reflect the Office's original filing arrangement: Historical, Office Files, Coded Files, Visual Materials, and Faculty Background Files.

scopecontent.p: The Historical series (1894-1995, 1 linear foot) consists of a miscellaneous assemblage of correspondence, reports and student memorabilia documenting the history of the College of Engineering. Research files include information on early women graduates and a survey of historical artifacts within the College of Engineering. The Engineering Communications & Marketing office compiled this material primarily for use in publications and at reunions. Several of the items were donated by engineering alumni and class officers.

scopecontent.p: The Office Files (1978-1997, 1.2 linear feet) series consists of correspondence, reports, and memos concerning the typical activities of the Office of Communications & Marketing. The series documents alumni activities, building dedications, commencement, fundraising, and other activities. It is organized alphabetically. Building dedications and groundbreakings include the Herbert H. Dow Building, Electrical Engineering and Computer Science (EECS) Building, Lurie Bell Tower, and Lurie Engineering Center.

scopecontent.p: Coded Files (1860-1994, 5 linear feet) retains the original color-coded filing scheme used by the Office of Communications & Marketing. The series is divided into subseries based on the color-code. Records include scripts, photographic material, reports, and newspaper articles. The first subseries, "Scripts," (1990-1993, 0.8 linear foot) contains written scripts for events and video productions such as the Francois-Xavier Bagnoud Building dedication, and the memorial for professor Shien-Ming Wu. The second subseries, "Buildings, Construction and Landscaping," (yellow dot) (1985-1991, 0.4 linear foot) contains photographs, slides, contact sheets, and negatives. The third subseries, "Computers Laboratories and Facilities" (blue dot) (1983-1993, 0.2 linear foot) consists of photographs, slides, contact sheets. The fourth and fifth subseries "Events" (orange dot) (1985-1993 0.8 linear foot) and "People" (red dot) (1968-1993, 1.0 linear foot) contain photographs, slides, contact sheets, and negatives. The subseries of "Miscellaneous coded material" (1987-1994, 0.2 linear foot) consists of three bound publications: "A Survey of Intellectual Activities," 1987, "Briefing for Regent Veronica L. Smith," 1988, and newspaper and magazine clippings about the University of Michigan College of Engineering, 1993-1994. The subseries, "Various Photographs and Slides" (purple dot) (1860-1993, 2.3 linear feet) contains topically arranged photographs coded with a purple dot and the subseries "Various Brochures and Programs" (green dot) (1987-1995, .5 linear feet) contains pamphlets, programs and photographs from different events coded with a green dot. Because the two subseries were accessioned later than the rest of the coded files, they are physically separate from the rest of the coded files.

scopecontent.p: The Visual Material series (1855-2010, bulk 1980-2000, 15.5 linear feet) consists of photographs, slides, and negatives documenting the history and activities of the College of Engineering. This material complements and extends the visual material contained in the earlier coded files series. The Visual Material was received in two separate transfers. The first installment of material designated by the unit as Visual Material was received between1995 and 1998 and comprises the contents of boxes 5-9. An additional 11 feet designated Visual Material by the unit was received in 2010 and comprises the contents of boxes 12-22.

The Visual Material series is divided into three subseries based upon the Office of Communications & Marketing organization of the records: "Photo Archives," "Slides," and "Photographs, Contact Sheets and Negatives." The "Photo Archives" subseries (1983-1987, 1.5 linear feet) contains a variety of numbered photographs and contact sheets, including photographs of College of Engineering facilities, faculty, students, special projects, and events. The index provides the appropriate labels for each number; however, the numbers are not always consecutive. "Slides" (ca. 1982-1989, 0.7 linear feet) depict College of Engineering facilities and special programs and projects. Some of the slides are labeled either on the slide or on the plastic sleeves housing the slides, but many do not have dates.

scopecontent.p: The "Photographs, Contact Sheets, and Negatives" subseries (1855-2010, 13.6 linear feet) consists of photographs of a wide variety of subjects. The subseries is subdivided into five sub-subseries or sub-categories: "Buildings and Research Facilities," "Events," "Faculty, Staff, Scholars and Donors," "Historical," "Student Life and School Activities," and "Other." The "Buildings and Research Facilities" sub-category (1965-1992, 0.5 linear feet) includes photographs of building construction, completed buildings and laboratories. "Events" (1927-1995, 1.1 linear foot) includes photographs of reunions, commencement, building dedications, conferences, lectures and other events. The Faculty, Staff, Scholars and Donors material (1926-1995, 0.5 linear foot) consists of photographs from staff and faculty gatherings and portraits of scholars, faculty and donors. The "Historical" grouping (1855-2000, 4.5 linear feet) consists of early photographs of the College of Engineering faculty, laboratories, and buildings, including several scrapbooks pertaining to Camp Davis. Other photographs include a series of World War I activities portraying members of the Student Army Training Corps (SATC). The Historical grouping is split into two due to a later addition in 2010 of related material. Those interested in the sub-subseries should check boxes 8-9 as well as boxes 12-14. "Student Life and School Activities" (1967-1997, 0.5 linear feet) contains photographs of student life from the 1960s to the 1990s. The "Other" grouping (1980-2010, 8 linear feet) contains photographs of buildings, people, events, and other college activities that cannot be easily classified under the headings named above.

scopecontent.p:
The Faculty Background Files (ca. 1980 -- ca. 2000, 12 linear feet) series consist of photographs, curriculum vitae, profiles, and news clippings of Engineering faculty from the early 1980s to the late 1990s. Each faculty member is identified by their departmental association, some of which are different than the College's current department names. The acronyms used are identified as:
AERO - Aerospace Engineering
AOSS - Atmospheric, Oceanic and Space Sciences
BiomedE - Biomedical Engineering
Chem - Chemical Engineering
CEE - Civil and Environmental Engineering
EECS - Electrical Engineering and Computer Science
IOE - Industrial and Operations Engineering
MSE - Materials Science and Engineering
MEAM - Mechanical Engineering and Applied Mechanics
NAME - Naval Architecture and Marine Engineering
NERS - Nuclear Engineering and Radiological Sciences
SPRL -- Space Physics Research Laboratory
